GARBAGE COLLECTION\
=====================\
\
MEMORY ISSUES\
\
Memory Leak			-	unused objects are never freed\
Dangling Reference		-	reference to an area of memory that has already been reclaimed	\
\
CONCEPTS\
\
Automatic/Implicit Memory Management\
\
\
Abandoned Object\
- an object with no active references\
- how \
	- object goes out of scope\
	- objects reference is assigned some other reference or a null value\
\
\
GC Specifics\
- runs in the background\
- there is no guarantee when gc runs\
- programmer can hint to JVM to run gc with System.gc() or Runtime.getRuntime().gc() (JVM may ignore this hint)\
- each gc cycle can cause pauses (stop-the-world) in application\
\
\
\
ALGORITHMS\
\
Challenges	-	 how to identify dead objects, how to minimize application pause\
\
\
Algorithm - Mark and Sweep\
Mark finds live objects\
Sweep removes abandoned ones\
\
\
Algorithm - Mark-Sweep-Compact\
like mark and sweep, memory area is compacted\
\
\
Algorithm - Mark and Copy\
instead of sweep, live objects are copied to a new memory area\
\
\
Algorithm	- Concurrent Mark and Sweep	(mostly runs concurrently with application, but can pause application)\
\
\
MEMORY DIVISIONS\
\
Generational Collection\
- java heap memory is divided into Young generation and Old (tenured) generation\
- objects get promoted from young generation to old generation\
- old generation collection is less frequent\
- garbage collection of young generation is young gc and for old generation is old gc\
- full gc involves both young and old generations\
\
\
Young generation memory is divided into\
- eden\
- from survivor\
- to survivor\
\
\
GC PROCESS\
When application first starts all objects on heap are created in eden part of young generation, the other parts of memory (young survivor and tenured) are empty\
gc cycle kicks in -  promotes eden objects to \'91to survivor\'92 (mark and copy)\
gc cycle ends - \'91to survivor\'92 objects are sent to \'91from survivor\'92	(eden and \'91to survivor\'92 are empty)\
application is working - eden is filling up \
gc cycle kicks in - eden and \'91from survivor\'92 objects are sent to \'91to survivor\'92\
gc cycle ends - \'91to survivor\'92 objects are sent to \'91from survivor\'92	(eden and \'91to survivor\'92 are empty)\
application is working - eden is filling up\
after X number of cycles a survivor object can be moved to old/tenured generation  (15 gc cycles default, depends on jvm, can be adjusted)\
\
Caveats\
in a gc cycle an object can go from eden to old generation if there is no space for it in \'91to survivor)\
\
\
Full GC kicks in - this is young gc + old gc + metaspace\
\
\
